&#xa0;
[normal]Law Commission – Written evidence[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Executive Summary
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The principal matters arising from the evidence of the Law Commission (“the Commission”) may be summarised as follows:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](1)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Law Commission (“the Commission”) shares the objectives of Government to make the law more accessible and to remove obsolete legislation from the statute book.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](2)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Commission has a statutory duty under section 3(1) of the Law Commissions Act 1965 to keep under review all the law of England and Wales with a view, inter alia, to the repeal of obsolete and unnecessary enactments. Since 1965 it has promoted the repeal of over 3000 statutes and many thousands of other provisions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](3)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In performing this work, the Commission has considerable experience and expertise, is able to employ a fast track Parliamentary procedure and has the trust of Parliament.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](4)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Triennial Review of the Commission concluded in July 2013 that it is essential that the Law Commission, an expert, independent body, should continue to perform this function
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](5)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The powers proposed in clauses 50-57, 62 and schedule 16 of the Bill duplicate the provisions in the Law Commissions Act 1965 and do not provide the advantages of the Commission’s statute law repeal procedure. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](6)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Commission is deeply concerned at the impact of being a statutory 
[normal]consultee
[normal].  It could not perform this role adequately and continue with its own repeal work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](7)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Given the specialist nature of statute law repeal work, the importance of accuracy and the need to have an in depth understanding of the consequences of repeal, the Commission proposes that the better course for primary legislation would be to adapt and improve the existing Statute Law Repeal procedure to meet changing needs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](8)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This would not require legislative change, would be more cost effective and provide legal certainty. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](9)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is preferable that the repeal of primary legislation be achieved by the existing Statute Law Repeal procedure employing an Act of Parliament as opposed to Ministerial powers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](10)
[normal] 
[normal]There already exist alternative mechanisms for the repeal of secondary legislation. For this reason the Commission does not currently focus on secondary legislation. It would not be able to perform adequately the role of statutory 
[normal]consultee
[normal] in relation to secondary legislation within existing resources.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The evidence ends with answers to certain specific questions posed by the Committee.  
[normal]&#xa0;
